00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.800
&gt;&gt; Swanee Hunt: I'm very,
very pleased to get asked this

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:19.340
because one of the lessons that
I draw out relates to this.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:21.960
So I can give you a good
bit of stats which is

00:45:21.960 --> 00:45:31.220
that illiteracy was at about 51%
for women before the genocide.

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:38.040
And now it's compulsory
education through ninth grade.

00:45:38.040 --> 00:45:41.880
And that is extraordinary.

00:45:41.880 --> 00:45:45.470
And that very much
affects, then,

00:45:45.470 --> 00:45:48.110
the whole emerging business.

00:45:48.110 --> 00:45:52.220
And because the women, when
they got into parliament,

00:45:52.220 --> 00:45:57.690
one of the first bills that
they passed was the right

00:45:57.690 --> 00:46:01.960
to inherit land and
then land reform.

00:46:01.960 --> 00:46:06.830
And you know, that
right to inherit land --

00:46:06.830 --> 00:46:09.630
you know, I never really had
a sense of what that meant,

00:46:09.630 --> 00:46:12.010
how important that was.

00:46:12.010 --> 00:46:13.310
That's like fundamental.

00:46:13.310 --> 00:46:18.930
When you are living in a
home and your husband dies

00:46:18.930 --> 00:46:22.770
and the whole home goes
to his brother or whatever

00:46:22.770 --> 00:46:26.550
and then you become
impoverished and --

00:46:26.550 --> 00:46:28.480
I mean, that's really basic.

00:46:28.480 --> 00:46:31.540
And you don't have
that home as collateral

00:46:31.540 --> 00:46:33.540
when you want to
start a business.

00:46:33.540 --> 00:46:37.850
So it's very much all connected.

00:46:37.850 --> 00:46:40.960
But the point I want to
hone in on when I look

00:46:40.960 --> 00:46:47.700
at other countries: there's
so much ado about the idea

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:50.770
that unless you have
a certain higher level

00:46:50.770 --> 00:46:56.230
of literacy you cannot have
women fully represented

00:46:56.230 --> 00:46:58.150
as leaders.

00:46:58.150 --> 00:46:59.800
That's just not true.

00:46:59.800 --> 00:47:01.540
I mean, do the arithmetic.

00:47:01.540 --> 00:47:03.520
It's not even math.

00:47:03.520 --> 00:47:05.360
Do the arithmetic.

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:12.650
How many women do you need to
have as significant leaders?

00:47:12.650 --> 00:47:18.480
100? 500? 4,000?

00:47:18.480 --> 00:47:19.780
Whatever? Right?

00:47:19.780 --> 00:47:25.040
Are you telling me that
there aren't 4,000 women

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:31.400
in any country on earth who
haven't had college degrees,

00:47:31.400 --> 00:47:34.540
masters, doctorates, who
haven't been extraordinarily

00:47:34.540 --> 00:47:37.030
well-experienced, who
haven't traveled the world?

00:47:37.030 --> 00:47:38.920
Of course there are.

00:47:38.920 --> 00:47:44.990
And so we have this false
relationship that we walk

00:47:44.990 --> 00:47:47.820
around thinking, oh well
this is a really, you know,

00:47:47.820 --> 00:47:52.060
this backward country
where women haven't had all

00:47:52.060 --> 00:47:53.390
of these opportunities,

00:47:53.390 --> 00:47:55.680
therefore they can't
be in leadership.

00:47:55.680 --> 00:47:56.980
Those two don't go together.

00:47:56.980 --> 00:48:01.990
Do you want to add to that, or?

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:04.800
&gt;&gt; Mathilde Mukantabana: One
tiny thing I can add that you -

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:09.710
whoops -- were to say it very
well but just what I'm going

00:48:09.710 --> 00:48:11.750
to add, especially
for Rwandan women,

00:48:11.750 --> 00:48:15.740
and you mentioned it
a lot and it's very,

00:48:15.740 --> 00:48:18.470
very important for
Rwandan women.

00:48:18.470 --> 00:48:21.180
But to think in terms
of after genocide,

00:48:21.180 --> 00:48:23.400
people didn't have anything.

00:48:23.400 --> 00:48:26.540
And among the things that were
done to empower the people,

00:48:26.540 --> 00:48:32.990
to make people wake up --
that economic leverage, basic,

00:48:32.990 --> 00:48:34.990
was part of the program.

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:37.780
It means that whatever
one has created

00:48:37.780 --> 00:48:40.050
or what the women
themselves have done,

00:48:40.050 --> 00:48:42.200
what we call homegrown
initiatives,

00:48:42.200 --> 00:48:47.320
there were socioeconomic
programs specifically targeting

00:48:47.320 --> 00:48:48.870
people with nothing.

00:48:48.870 --> 00:48:52.850
Like for instance, what they
call getting a, have a cow.

00:48:52.850 --> 00:48:54.150
Where do they distribute
the cows?

00:48:54.150 --> 00:48:56.630
The sort of poorest
families can have

00:48:56.630 --> 00:48:59.580
at least a basic,
basic beginning.

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:00.880
All the elements

00:49:00.880 --> 00:49:02.280
of reconciliation
among women started

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:06.150
with economic initiatives, like
what they call peace baskets.

00:49:06.150 --> 00:49:08.940
When they get together,
they do stuff together.

00:49:08.940 --> 00:49:11.880
They bring a certain
economic livelihood

00:49:11.880 --> 00:49:16.490
but at the same time they are
coming together as people.

00:49:16.490 --> 00:49:20.320
So those are the things that
when you address your attention

00:49:20.320 --> 00:49:24.180
to the health issues -- you
know, people were dying.

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:28.450
And the promotion of universal
health coverage was for that.

00:49:28.450 --> 00:49:29.830
People were dying.

00:49:29.830 --> 00:49:31.470
Even if you survived --

00:49:31.470 --> 00:49:33.370
sometimes they were
dying from AIDS/HIV.

00:49:33.370 --> 00:49:35.910
They were dying from
tuberculosis.

00:49:35.910 --> 00:49:37.980
They were dying from
many diseases.

00:49:37.980 --> 00:49:40.650
So tackling the issues of
health, tackling the issues

00:49:40.650 --> 00:49:45.940
of poverty were also a big part
of our reconstruction efforts

00:49:45.940 --> 00:49:48.370
that the women promoted.

00:49:48.370 --> 00:49:49.730
Thank you.

