have another cup of coffee

00:53:29.540 --> 00:53:31.700
and then have another
cup of coffee

00:53:31.700 --> 00:53:33.170
and have another cup of coffee.

00:53:33.170 --> 00:53:36.000
And I was going on
and telling him

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:39.930
about how this is the moment.

00:53:39.930 --> 00:53:45.140
This is the moment you need
to bring women in to the core

00:53:45.140 --> 00:53:49.610
of what you're doing through
our forces because if you want

00:53:49.610 --> 00:53:56.730
to stabilize, those women know
which disaffected teenagers --

00:53:56.730 --> 00:54:00.700
these boys have a weapon
under their mattress.

00:54:00.700 --> 00:54:05.050
These women are the ones who are
perceived as less threatening.

00:54:05.050 --> 00:54:09.510
So they can get into places
where the men can't get.

00:54:09.510 --> 00:54:12.520
These are the ones who
have a whole history

00:54:12.520 --> 00:54:15.810
of working across lines.

00:54:15.810 --> 00:54:18.650
And I went on and on.

00:54:18.650 --> 00:54:22.860
And he listened very
attentively.

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:28.080
And I said, you know, they have
tremendous leadership skills

00:54:28.080 --> 00:54:29.380
that you can tap.

00:54:29.380 --> 00:54:31.690
These are untapped resources.

00:54:31.690 --> 00:54:33.650
And he listened some more
and he nods his head.

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:36.080
And then he said,
"Madam Ambassador,

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:39.340
I cannot thank you
enough for coming

00:54:39.340 --> 00:54:41.610
and I appreciate your time.

00:54:41.610 --> 00:54:47.330
And I want to assure
you that as soon

00:54:47.330 --> 00:54:50.780
as we can get the place
secure we can think

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:52.930
about women's issues."

00:54:52.930 --> 00:54:56.870
And I thought, I am not
talking about cervical cancer.

00:54:56.870 --> 00:54:58.430
I am talking about security.

00:54:58.430 --> 00:55:04.640
Well, to think how hard it is to
-- I mean, he gave me the time.

00:55:04.640 --> 00:55:08.040
I said all the right
things but it's that context

00:55:08.040 --> 00:55:11.150
that he didn't have, Don,
that you're talking about.

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:13.700
And he was a good guy.

00:55:13.700 --> 00:55:16.990
He wanted to understand
but he just --

00:55:16.990 --> 00:55:18.430
he was looking at it
from a different lens.

00:55:18.430 --> 00:55:23.560
And that's what we mean
by inclusive security.

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:25.980
We actually have
to look at security

00:55:25.980 --> 00:55:32.030
through a different lens that
includes the women of Rwanda.

00:55:32.030 --> 00:55:35.320
You know, not as these
women who need our help.

00:55:35.320 --> 00:55:36.620
That's the problem.

00:55:36.620 --> 00:55:37.920
We see them as victims.

00:55:37.920 --> 00:55:40.560
And you see this all the time.

00:55:40.560 --> 00:55:43.830
Where do you hear about the
women leaders in any depth?

00:55:43.830 --> 00:55:47.390
You hear about them as
victims, you know, and how,

00:55:47.390 --> 00:55:49.040
oh well they became leaders

00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:51.660
because so many men
had been killed.

00:55:51.660 --> 00:55:54.200
That's not why they
became leaders.

00:55:54.200 --> 00:55:57.530
I mean, that was one of the
circumstances among many

00:55:57.530 --> 00:56:02.100
in which sparked all
kinds of their leadership.

00:56:02.100 --> 00:56:05.830
But they were surging
into a chasm

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:09.620
when the chaos cracked
open the culture.

